way.\n< Nicola >

indulgence...\n< Nicola >

respectable adult.\n< Serena >

Especially compared to the likes of the city
guard.\n< Serena >

Yes. I knew the victim of a certain murder case.
Because of that, they accused me of being the
culprit.\n< Serena >

They threatened me... said if I wanted to be
exonerated, I should denounce Lord Nicola. They
wanted me to testify that you were the murderer.\n< Serena >
...So, how did you get out of that situation?\n< Nicola >

It was just when I had made the acquaintance of a
certain influential person in town... I mentioned
their name and was released.\n< Serena >

The visit was actually a secondary matter; I came
today to report this to you.\n< Serena >

I felt bad for bringing it up while you were
unwell, but given the circumstances, I thought it
best to inform you sooner rather than later.\n< Serena >
You're really conscientious, aren't you?\n< Nicola >

No, I'm sorry. It's my fault that you were
troubled because of me. The city guard must be
desperate. After all, we've raised our neighbor's
status in front of them.\n< Nicola >

Indeed. They seem desperate to smear the patrol

The patrol guards are directly under His Majesty
the King. Only His Majesty has judicial authority.
Even if I committed a crime, the city doesn't have
the authority to judge me...\n< Nicola >

Ah, perhaps that's their aim. If I avoid
prosecution due to my privileges, people's eyes
will inevitably turn 'there.'\n< Nicola >

His Majesty and the Free City are in a tense
situation over the city charter. Regardless of the
truth... if it looks like I, a royalist, am
flaunting my privileges, the citizens will harbor
resentment.\n< Nicola >

The reputation of the patrol guards will fall, and
any criticism of the city guard will be drowned

political conflict. Despicable people indeed.\n< Serena >

Well, we don't exactly want to set off a bomb

I've been delayed by the aftermath and feeling
unwell... but it seems we can't afford to talk

I can't afford to trouble you, Serena-kun, any

What do you say, Serena-kun? Are you sure you

It's a tempting offer, but I must decline. This

That was careless of me. I took the conversation
in the wrong direction...\n< Nicola >
...Well then. Let's leave it at that for now.\n< Nicola >

Thank you, Serena-kun. I've caused you concern.
I'm fine now. I'll return to work.\n< Nicola >
Good. Then it was worth coming to see you.\n< Serena >

...Lord Nicola, it's good to see you well. I
really like that person after all.\n< Serena >

They remind me somewhat of Lady Erika. Their
frankness... straightforward and admirable.\n< Serena >

Lady Erika... speaking of which, I wonder how she
is doing. Once I find the Splendor, before
returning to Gratzia, I'd like to visit her.\n< Serena >

But first... I must resolve the immediate problems
at hand.\n< Serena >

The room I took is next to the stairs. Not this
one.\n< Serena >
It's locked. Well, of course.\n< Serena >
Should I take it off for today?\n< Serena >

to walk outside dressed like this...\n< Serena >

again... I hate it. It's embarrassing... I don't
want this...\n< Serena >

out, the city guards will... do terrible things
again...\n< Serena >

It's okay... As long as they don't find out, it's
okay. I'll make sure to stay away from those
guys...\n< Serena >

Wh-why am I not wearing panties?! It's unthinkable

or anything.\n< Serena >

If someone from home saw me in such a shameful
outfit, they'd scold me... No, maybe I'm not even
worth that much anymore...\n< Serena >

To be seen in such a shameful outfit by someone
from home, I'd get scolded. Have I become a bit of
a bad girl?\n< Serena >
I need to pay for the lodging first...\n< Serena >
